<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="465" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,566,843]" pageId="14" pageNumber="465">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,566,591]" pageId="14" pageNumber="465">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The apical maxillary palpomere is triangular and expanded towards the apex (Fig. 
<number box="[1275,1290,566,591]" pageId="14" pageNumber="465" value="6.0">6</number>
E), a unique character among the genera of the tribe. Furthermore, members of the genus can be recognized by the following: clypeus triangular, strongly narrowed towards apex, with 
<number box="[853,867,639,663]" pageId="14" pageNumber="465" value="2.0">2</number>
apical teeth; frontal carina evident; mandibles tridentate; protibia with 
<number box="[422,436,675,699]" pageId="14" pageNumber="465" value="3.0">3</number>
teeth; males with protarsi not enlarged.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="465" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,566,843]" pageId="14" pageNumber="465">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,710,735]" pageId="14" pageNumber="465">Distribution.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[361,517,710,735]" class="Insecta" family="Dynastidae" genus="Hylobothynus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="465" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[361,517,710,735]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="465">Hylobothynus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is mainly an Amazonian genus (
<bibRefCitation author="Ratcliffe" box="[893,1060,710,735]" pageId="14" pageNumber="465" refString="Ratcliffe, B. C. (1981) The fourth Hylobothynus: spanning the Amazonian gap (Coleoptera: Scarabaeidae: Dynastinae). The Coleopterists Bulletin, 35, 303 - 306." type="journal article" year="1981">
Ratcliffe 
<number box="[1001,1060,711,735]" pageId="14" pageNumber="465" value="1981.0">1981</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), currently containing five South American species; one from 
<collectingCountry box="[498,673,746,771]" name="French Guiana" pageId="14" pageNumber="465">French Guiana</collectingCountry>
; two from 
<collectingCountry box="[814,927,746,771]" name="Colombia" pageId="14" pageNumber="465">Colombia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[945,1040,746,771]" name="Ecuador" pageId="14" pageNumber="465">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
, and 
<collectingCountry box="[1111,1166,747,770]" name="Peru" pageId="14" pageNumber="465">Peru</collectingCountry>
; and two from 
<collectingCountry box="[1361,1433,746,771]" name="Brazil" pageId="14" pageNumber="465">Brazil</collectingCountry>
. However, these species are not common in 
<collectingCountry box="[662,775,782,807]" name="Colombia" pageId="14" pageNumber="465">Colombia</collectingCountry>
, and there have been no recent collections, so only 
<typeStatus box="[1388,1436,783,807]" pageId="14" pageNumber="465">type</typeStatus>
material was available. Therefore, only a diagnosis is shown for each species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
